liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Another upset is on the cards in Group A, with the World Cup debutants in the lead against the tournament co-hosts. All the talk before the game was about how the Football Ferns could just about lock up a knockout spot with a win this afternoon, but suddenly the Philippines have thrown that into disarray. Sarina Bolden's goal was the result of near-perfect attacking play from Philippines, with Sara Eggesvik's cross put perfectly in her path and the leap and header was clean. New Zealand will be disappointed by the efforts of defenders CJ Bott and Rebekah Stott, while goalie Victoria Esson got both hands to it right in front of her face but couldn't handle. New Zealand beat Norway in their opener, and now if this game stays like this, the group is completely wide open. Especially if Norway beat Switzerland tonight, then every team in the group will be on one win each!

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Sarina Bolden has scored the Philippines' first-ever World Cup goal, leaping above the Kiwi defenders to head home an excellent cross. It was completely against the run of play, because the Ferns have been in control of basically the entire match so far, but couldn't handle the attacking raid from the Filipinas. A long free-kick came in and it was headed clear but to the feet of Sara Eggesvik, who turned, beat a defender and put the cross in perfectly between CJ Bott and Rebekah Stott, with Bolden leaping into that gap and getting a shot on target. It was straight at goalkeeper Victoria Esson, but she couldn't handle the close-range effort and the ball found the back of the net.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 24' Philippines hit the lead against New Zealand and make some history!

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It was a better session for the Australian share market today, with the ASX 200 gaining half a per cent by the close of trade. And that's despite only 86 stocks on the benchmark index making a gain. There were some big gains where it mattered, with Fortescue (+4.6%), Rio Tinto (+3.4%), BHP (+3.3%) and South32 (+3.5%) leading the materials and giving a big boost to the market, while Woodside (+1.2%) and Whitehaven (+2.2%) rose in the energy sector. With local earnings season looming, though, the iron ore miners could soon come under pressure again — Rio Tinto will release its results after the close tomorrow and half-year earnings are expected to have fallen. Consumer stocks were not so buoyant — the big supermarkets Woolworths (-0.5%) and Coles (-0.3%) made modest losses while Wesfarmers dropped 0.9 per cent — the retailer said it will be merging the back-end operations of Target and Kmart. The major banks also ended in the red.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX ends up on iron ore surge

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: As recommended by the recent Reserve Bank review and confirmed by outgoing governor Philip Lowe a few weeks ago, the RBA board will meet just eight times next year, down from its current 11 meetings. Now, the RBA has released the schedule for its extended two-day meetings, which will see the new governor Michele Bullock hold a press conference after each decision is announced. While it will mean interest rate changes less often, it could also see the RBA board make bigger moves on occasion, according to some analysts. The 2024 meetings will be held on: 5–6 February 18–19 March 6–7 May 17–18 June 5–6 August 23–24 September 4–5 November 9–10 December
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: When will the Reserve Bank board meet next year?
